==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: physiology
<hw>phys`i*ol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(f⟦icr⟧z`⟦icr⟧*⟦ocr⟧l"⟦osl⟧*j⟦ycr⟧)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Physiologies</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>physiologia</ets>, Gr.
<grk>fysiologi`a</grk>; <grk>fy`sis</grk> nature + <grk>lo`gos</grk>
discourse: cf. F. <ets>physiologie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
science which treats of the phenomena of living organisms; the study of
the processes incidental to, and characteristic of, life.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ It is divided into <xex>animal</xex> and <xex>vegetable
physiology</xex>, dealing with animal and vegetable life respectively.
When applied especially to a study of the functions of the organs and
tissues in man, it is called <xex>human physiology</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A treatise on physiology.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mental physiology</b></col>, <cd>the science of the
functions and phenomena of the mind, as distinguished from a
philosophical explanation of the same.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Physiophyly</ent>⟦br⟧
